# Spec 004 — Backend Hardening for Public Exposure

Status: Draft
Owner: <you>
Related: 001-mvp (R5 key safety), 003-commute-depth (isochrone proxy), 006-deployment

## Overview

The backend currently proxies two paid Mapbox APIs (Isochrone, Geocoding) with
no rate limiting, no geographic fence, and no upstream spending cap, and it
re-serializes multi-megabyte GeoJSON on every request. Before the app is
exposed on a public URL, the proxy must be abuse-resistant (a bot must not be
able to drain the Mapbox quota), responses must be cacheable, and failures must
be observable and graceful. This spec hardens the existing API without changing
its shape: no endpoint paths, response schemas, or frontend code change.

## Context

- Each live `/api/isochrone` request triggers up to 3 upstream Mapbox calls
  (off-peak / typical / peak scenarios). The in-process 24 h TTL cache only
  helps for repeated identical coordinates; the raw key uses 6-decimal
  rounding (~10 cm), so every pin micro-drag is a cache miss.
- The deployment target (spec 006) is a single always-on container behind the
  platform's reverse proxy, so in-process rate limiting and caching are
  sufficient — no Redis needed at this scale.
- The platform terminates TLS and forwards the client IP in `X-Forwarded-For`.

## Requirements

- **R1 — Per-IP rate limiting.** Token-spending endpoints (`/api/isochrone`,
  `/api/geocode`) are limited to 10 requests/minute per client IP; data
  endpoints (`/api/housing`, `/api/zips.geojson`, `/api/regions`) to 60/minute.
  Exceeding the limit returns 429. The client IP is taken from the first entry
  of `X-Forwarded-For` when present (the platform proxy sets it), else the
  socket peer.
- **R2 — Geofence + origin snapping.** `/api/isochrone` rejects (422) work
  locations outside the union of loaded-region bounding boxes (+0.5° buffer).
  Before the cache key and any Mapbox call, the origin is snapped to a 0.005°
  (~500 m) grid, bounding worst-case unique-key cardinality and turning pin
  micro-drags into cache hits. ~500 m is visually irrelevant at 15–60-minute
  contour scale. `/api/geocode` remains constrained to `country=us`.
- **R3 — Daily upstream budget breaker.** A process-wide daily counter caps
  total upstream Mapbox calls (`MAPBOX_DAILY_CALL_BUDGET`, default 2000; 0
  disables). When exhausted, `/api/isochrone` serves a stale cached payload if
  one exists, else 503; `/api/geocode` returns 503. Cache hits spend nothing.
- **R4 — HTTP caching + compression.** `/api/zips.geojson` is pre-serialized
  once per state (no per-request re-serialization) and served with a strong
  `ETag` and `Cache-Control: public, max-age=86400`; `If-None-Match` returns
  304\. `/api/housing` carries the same validator semantics; `/api/regions`
  carries `Cache-Control`. Responses ≥1 KB are gzip-compressed when the client
  accepts it.
- **R5 — Structured request logging.** Every API request logs method, path,
  status, duration (ms), and client IP. `LOG_FORMAT=json` switches all app
  logs to single-line JSON for cloud log ingestion; default stays
  human-readable. Health-probe requests are not logged. The Mapbox token never
  appears in any log line (001-R5 preserved).
- **R6 — Meaningful health check.** `/api/health` verifies the region index
  parses and at least one state store loads; returns
  `{status, version, states}` with 200, or 503 when data is unavailable. Stays
  fast after first call (stores are cached) — it is the platform's probe.
- **R7 — Graceful data failure.** A missing or corrupt state data file yields
  a 503 with a clean detail message for that state only — never a 500
  traceback; other states keep working.

## Non-functional / Constraints

- No new infrastructure (no Redis, no database); all state is in-process.
- No endpoint path or response-schema changes; the frontend is untouched.
- Rate-limit ceilings and the daily budget are env-tunable without code edits.
- All Mapbox-token handling rules from 001-R5 continue to hold.

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Hammering `/api/isochrone` past 10 req/min from one IP returns 429, and
      upstream Mapbox call count stays flat (verified via logs/mock).
- [ ] An out-of-coverage origin (e.g. lat=0, lon=0) returns 422 with a clear
      message; two origins <500 m apart produce one set of upstream calls.
- [ ] With the daily budget exhausted, `/api/isochrone` returns stale-cache or
      503 and makes zero upstream calls.
- [ ] Second request to `/api/zips.geojson` with `If-None-Match` returns 304;
      responses are gzipped when `Accept-Encoding: gzip` is sent.
- [ ] A corrupted state file produces 503 for that state; `/api/health`
      reports 503 when no data loads and 200 with state count otherwise.
- [ ] `pytest` passes with new tests covering each behavior above; `ruff
      check` is clean.

## Out of Scope (explicit)

- Authentication / API keys for end users.
- Redis or any shared cache across processes.
- CDN configuration (spec 006 may add platform-level caching).
- Frontend changes of any kind (spec 005).

## Verification notes

429 → R1; out-of-bounds 422 + snap cache hit → R2; budget 503/stale → R3;
ETag/304/gzip → R4; log lines → R5; health 200/503 → R6; corrupt-file 503 →
R7. Verify manually with curl against a local server plus the automated tests;
the implementing agent does not self-certify done.
